#Allegro5.AL_FIXED
Allegro provides some routines for working with fixed point numbers, and defines the type @code(AL_FIXED) to be a signed 32-bit integer.  The high word is used for the integer part and the low word for the fraction, giving a range of -32768 to 32767 and an accuracy of about four or five decimal places.  Fixed point numbers can be assigned, compared, added, subtracted, negated and shifted (for multiplying or dividing by powers of two) using the normal integer operators, but you should take care to use the appropriate conversion routines when mixing fixed point with integer or floating point values. Writing @code(fixed_point_1 + fixed_point_2) is OK, but @code(fixed_point + integer) is not.

The only advantage of fixed point math routines is that you don't require a floating point coprocessor to use them.  This was great in the time period of i386 and i486 machines, but stopped being so useful with the coming of the Pentium class of processors.  From Pentium onwards, CPUs have increased their strength in floating point operations, equaling or even surpassing integer math performance.

Depending on the type of operations your program may need, using floating point types may be faster than fixed types if you are targeting a specific machine class. Many embedded processors have no FPUs so fixed point maths can be useful there.
@seealso(al_itofix) @seealso(al_fixtoi) @seealso(al_fixtrunc) @seealso(al_ftofix) @seealso(al_fixtof)
@seealso(al_fixadd) @seealso(al_fixsub) @seealso(al_fixmul) @seealso(al_fixdiv)
@seealso(al_fixsqrt)
@seealso(al_fixcos) @seealso(al_fixsin) @seealso(al_fixtan)

#Allegro5.AL_FIXTORAD_R
Example:
@longcode(!
var
  RadAngle, BinaryAngle: AL_FIXED;
begin
...

{ Set the binary angle to 90 degrees. }
  BinaryAngle := 64;
{ Now convert to radians (about 1.57). }
  RadAngle = al_fixmul (BinaryAngle, AL_FIXTORAD_R);
...
end.
!)
@seealso(AL_FIXED) @seealso(al_fixmul) @seealso(AL_RADTOFIX_R)
#Allegro5.AL_RADTOFIX_R
Example:
@longcode(!
var
  RadAngle, BinaryAngle: AL_FIXED;
begin
  BinaryAngle := al_fixmul (RadAngle, AL_RADTOFIX_R)
end.
!)
@seealso(AL_FIXED) @seealso(al_fixmul) @seealso(AL_FIXTORAD_R)

#Allegro5.al_fixsqrt
If `x' is negative, @link(al_get_errno) is set to @link(AL_EDOM) and the function returns zero.
#Allegro5.al_fixhypot
This should be better than calculating the formula yourself manually, since the error is much smaller.
#Allegro5.al_fixatan
The input value must be a fixed point radian.  The inverse tangent is the value whose tangent is x.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  InverseTangent: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ Sets InverseTangent to binary angle 13. }
  InverseTangent := al_fixatan (al_ftofix (0.326))
en.
!)
@return(The inverse tangent of a fixed point value, measured as a fixed point binary format angle.)
@seealso(al_fixtan) @seealso(al_fixatan2)
#Allegro5.al_fixatan2
Computes the arc tangent of @code(y / x), but the signs of both arguments are used to determine the quadrant of the result, and @code(x) is permitted to be zero.  This function is useful to convert Cartesian coordinates to polar coordinates.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  ResultValue: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ Sets ResultValue to binary angle 64. }
  ResultValue := al_fixatan2 (al_itofix (1), 0);
{ Sets ResultValue to binary angle -109. }
  ResultValue ::= al_fixatan2 (al_itofix (-1), al_itofix (-2));
{ Fails. }
  ResultValue := al_fixatan2 (0, 0);
  if al_get_errno <> 0 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@return(The arc tangent of y / x in fixed point binary format angle, from -128 to 128. If both x and y are zero, returns zero and sets Allegro's errno to @link(AL_EDOM).)
@seealso(al_fixtan) @seealso(al_fixatan)

#Allegro5.al_ftofix
Unlike @link(al_itofix), this function clamps values which could overflow the type conversion, setting @link(al_get_errno) to non-zero in the process if this happens.
@seealso(al_itofix) @seealso(al_fixtof)
#Allegro5.al_fixtof
@seealso(al_ftofix)

#Allegro5.al_fixadd
Although fixed point numbers can be added with the normal '+' integer operator, that doesn't provide any protection against overflow.  If overflow is a problem, you should use this function instead.  It is slower than using integer operators, but if an overflow occurs it will set @link(al_get_errno) and clamp the result, rather than just letting it wrap.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 5035 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixadd (al_itofix (5000), al_itofix (35));
{ Sets errno and puts -32768 into Value. }
  Value = al_fixadd (al_itofix (-31000), al_itofix (-3000));
{ This will fail. }
  if al_get_errno <> 0 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@returns(The clamped result of adding x to y, setting Allegro's errno to @link(AL_ERANGE) if there was an overflow.)
@seealso(al_fixsub) @seealso(al_fixmul) @seealso(al_fixdiv)
#Allegro5.al_fixsub
Although fixed point numbers can be substracted with the normal '-' integer operator, that doesn't provide any protection against overflow.  If overflow is a problem, you should use this function instead.  It is slower than using integer operators, but if an overflow occurs it will set @link(al_get_errno) and clamp the result, rather than just letting it wrap.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 4965 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixsub (al_itofix (5000), al_itofix (35));
{ Sets errno and puts -32768 into Value. }
  Value = al_fixsub (al_itofix (-31000), al_itofix (3000));
{ This will fail. }
  if al_get_errno <> 0 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@returns(The clamped result of substracting y from x, setting Allegro's errno to @link(AL_ERANGE) if there was an overflow.)
@seealso(al_fixadd) @seealso(al_fixmul) @seealso(al_fixdiv)
#Allegro5.al_fixmul
A fixed point value can be multiplied or divided by an integer with the normal * and / operators.  To multiply two fixed point values, though, you must use this function.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 30000 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixmul (al_itofix (10), al_itofix (3000))
end.
!)
@return(The clamped result of multiplying x by y.)
@seealso(al_fixadd) @seealso(al_fixsub) @seealso(al_fixdiv)
#Allegro5.al_fixdiv
A fixed point value can be divided by an integer with the normal / operator.  To divide two fixed point values, though, you must use this function.  If a division by zero occurs, Allegro's errno will be set and the maximum possible value will be returned, but errno is not cleared if the operation is successful.  This means that if you are going to test for division by zero you should call @code(@link(al_set_errno) @(0@)) before calling @code(al_fixdiv).

Example:

@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 0.06060 Value. }
  Value := al_fixdiv (al_itofix (2), al_itofix (33));
{ This will put 0 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixdiv (0, al_itofix (-30));
{ Sets errno and puts -32768 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixdiv (al_itofix (-100), al_itofix (0));
  if al_get_errno <> 0 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@return(The result of dividing x by y. If y is zero, returns the maximum possible fixed point value and sets Allegro's errno to @link(AL_ERANGE).)
@seealso(al_fixadd) @seealso(al_fixsub) @seealso(al_fixmul)

#Allegro5.al_fixfloor
That is, it rounds towards negative infinity.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Number: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 33 into Number. }
  Number := al_fixfloor (al_itofix (100) / 3);
{ And this will round down to 16. }
  Number := al_fixfloor (al_itofix (100) / 6)
end.
!)
@seealso(al_fixtoi) @seealso(al_fixceil)
#Allegro5.al_fixceil
That is, it rounds towards positive infinity.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Number: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 34 into Number. }
  Number := al_fixceil (al_itofix (100) / 3);
{ And this will round down to 17. }
  Number := al_fixceil (al_itofix (100) / 6)
end.
!)
@seealso(al_fixtoi) @seealso(al_fixfloor)
#Allegro5.al_itofix
This is the same thing as @code(x shl 16).  Remember that overflows (trying to convert an integer greater than 32767) and underflows (trying to convert an integer lesser than -32768) are not detected even in debug builds!  The values simply "wrap around".

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Number: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This conversion is OK. }
  Number := al_itofix (100);
  if al_fixtoi (number) <> 100 then Halt (-1);
{ This is not OK. }
  Number := al_itofix (64000);
  if al_fixtoi (number) <> 64000 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@returns(The value of the integer converted to fixed point ignoring overflows.)
@seealso(al_fixtoi) @seealso(al_ftofix) @seealso(al_fixtof)
#Allegro5.al_fixtoi)
Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ This will put 33 into Value. }
  Value := al_fixtoi (al_itofix (100) div 3);
{ But this will round up to 17. }
  Value := al_fixtoi (al_itofix (100) div 6)
end.
!)
@seealso(al_itofix) @seealso(al_fixtrunc)
#Allegro5.al_fixtrunc
@seealso(al_fixtoi) @seealso(al_itofix)

#Allegro5.al_fixcos
The input value must be a @html(<a href="introduction.html#fix_trig">fixed point binary angle</a>).

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Angle: AL_FIXED;
  Value: Real;
begin
{ Set the binary angle to 45 degrees. }
  Angle := al_itofix (32);
{ The cosine of 45 degrees is about 0.7071. }
  Value := al_fixtof (al_fixcos (Angle));
  if not ((Value > 0.7) and (Value < 0.71)) then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@return(The cosine of a fixed point binary format angle.)
@seealso(al_fixsin) @seealso(al_fixacos)
#Allegro5.al_fixsin
The input value must be a @html(<a href="introduction.html#fix_trig">fixed point binary angle</a>).

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Angle: AL_FIXED;
  Value: Real;
begin
{ Set the binary angle to 90 degrees. }
  Angle := al_itofix (64);
{ The sine of 90 degrees is about one. }
  Value := al_fixtof (al_fixsin (Angle));
  if Value <> 1 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@return(The cosine of a fixed point binary format angle.)
@seealso(al_fixcos) @seealso(al_fixasin)
#Allegro5.al_fixtan
The input value must be a @html(<a href="introduction.html#fix_trig">fixed point binary angle</a>).

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Angle: AL_FIXED, ResA, ResB;
  Dif: Real;
begin
  Angle := al_itofix (37);
{ Prove that tan (angle) = sin (angle) / cos (angle). }
  ResA := al_fixdiv (al_fixsin (Angle), al_fixcos (Angle));
  ResB := al_fixtan (Angle);
  Dif := al_fixtof (al_fixsub (ResA, ResB));
  WriteLn (Format ('Precision error: %f', [Dif]))
end.
!)
@return(The tangent of a fixed point binary format angle.)
@seealso(al_fixatan) @seealso(al_fixcos) @seealso(al_fixsin)
#Allegro5.al_fixacos
The inverse cosine is defined only in the domain from -1 to 1.  Outside of this input range, the function will set Allegro's errno to @link(AL_EDOM) and return zero.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ Sets Value to binary angle 128. }
  Value = al_fixacos (al_itofix (-1))
end.
!)
@return(The inverse cosine of a fixed point value, measured as fixed point binary format angle, or zero if the input was out of range.  All return values of this function will be in the range 0 to 128.)
@seealso(al_fixcos) @seealso(al_get_errno)
#Allegro5.al_fixasin
The inverse sine is defined only in the domain from -1 to 1.  Outside of this input range, the function will set Allegro's errno to @link(AL_EDOM) and return zero.

Example:
@longcode(!
var
  Angle: Real;
  Value: AL_FIXED;
begin
{ Sets Value to right binary angle (64). }
  Value = al_fixasin (al_itofix (1))
{ Sets Angle to 0.2405. }
  Angle := al_fixtof (al_fixmul (al_fixasin (al_ftofix (0.238)), AL_FIXTORAD_R));
{ This will trigger the if. }
  Value := al_fixasin (al_ftofix (-1.09));
  if al_get_errno <> 0 then Halt (-1)
end.
!)
@return(The inverse sine of a fixed point value, measured as fixed point binary format angle, or zero if the input was out of range.  All return values of this function will be in the range 0 to 128.)
@seealso(al_fixsin) @seealso(al_get_errno)



